## 2. ARCHITECTURE RULES (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
- All business logic lives in /src/lib. All UI components in /src/components.
- Server-side DB access: use Supabase anon key (NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY) from /src/lib/supabase.ts.
- Admin API routes (/api/admin/*) are protected by Edge Middleware JWT check in /src/middleware.ts.
- Site settings are stored in Supabase table `site_settings` as key-value JSONB pairs. Key 'site' holds siteSettings object, key 'banner' holds banner config.
- The SiteContext (/src/context/SiteContext.tsx) is populated server-side in layout.tsx and provides static SSR data to components. For live data, components must fetch directly from Supabase client-side.
- NEVER use 'any' TypeScript type. Define proper interfaces.
- NEVER hardcode secrets. All keys must be in .env.local (see .env.example).

## 3. DATABASE (SUPABASE) — CRITICAL FACTS
- ALWAYS use supabase_master.sql (root of project) as the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for schema + RLS policies.
- RLS is PERMISSIVE: all tables allow full public access (SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE USING true). This is intentional — admin protection is handled by Next.js JWT middleware, not DB-level auth.
- Tables: site_settings, gallery, blog, reviews, leads, site_events, categories.
- site_settings key names: 'site' (main settings), 'banner' (banner config). NEVER use 'siteSettings' key.
- gallery table uses TEXT[] for image_urls (array), NOT a single image_url column.
- site_events table columns: event_type, path, referrer, source. NO 'detail' column.
- Storage bucket name: 'site-media' (public). Set in NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_STORAGE_BUCKET.
- If DB operations fail silently, first suspect RLS policies blocking the anon key. Run supabase_master.sql to reset.

